      <hedline>
        <hl1>Curb the Spread of Nuclear Arms</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>J P Smith letter contends July 27 editorial improperly omitted discussion of Israel's nuclear program</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Nuclear Breakout'' (editorial, July 27):</p>
        <p>I agree with your general premise that the Bush administration is not focusing on one of the more alarming security issues facing the world today. But what I find interesting is what you omitted: the Israeli nuclear program.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Nuclear Breakout'' (editorial, July 27):</p>
        <p>I agree with your general premise that the Bush administration is not focusing on one of the more alarming security issues facing the world today. But what I find interesting is what you omitted: the Israeli nuclear program.</p>
        <p>How Israel managed to join the ''nuclear club'' has been the road map for all other countries to follow. And I find it na√Øve to think that other Middle Eastern countries would not try to obtain some sort of parity (a rationale that the United States used throughout the cold war).</p>
        <p>If the United States is to play the role of good cop in the area of nuclear policy, it is important to place Israel's nuclear stockpile on the table. Until then, the nuclear breakout problem will remain.</p>
        <p>J. P. SMITH  Brooklyn, July 27, 2003</p>
      </block>
